	<p><a href="http://blog.twitter.com/2010/09/better-twitter.html">Twitter:</a></p> <blockquote><p>“Today, we’re introducing a new, re-engineered <a href="http://Twitter.com"></a><a href="http://Twitter.com">Twitter.com</a> that provides an easier, faster, and richer experience.”</p></blockquote> <p>This is a smart move. It helps them on two fronts: bringing in more brand marketers and newbies.</p> <p>Twitter had been stuck. They are growing significantly for sure – but all of it is coming off a small base of active users.</p> <p>The redesign gives marketers more flexibility in design and newbies a reason to stay longer. This – over time – will turn them from passive users into more active ones that tweet.</p> <p>It’s what they had to do get out of neutral gear.</p> <p></p>
	
